{"id":"2009.13985","submitter":"Raphael Yuster","authors":"Raphael Yuster","title":"Paths with many shortcuts in tournaments","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1016/j.disc.2020.112168","report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A shortcut of a directed path $v_1 v_2 \\cdots v_n$ is an edge $v_iv_j$ with\n$j > i+1$. If $j = i+2$ the shortcut is called a hop. If all hops are present,\nthe path is called hop complete, so the path and its hops form a square of a\npath. We prove that every tournament with $n \\ge 4$ vertices has a Hamiltonian\npath with at least $(4n-10)/7$ hops, and has a hop complete path of order at\nleast $n^{0.295}$.\n  A spanning binary tree of a tournament is a spanning shortcut tree if for\nevery vertex of the tree, all its left descendants are in-neighbors and all its\nright descendants are out-neighbors. It is well-known that every tournament\ncontains a spanning shortcut tree. The number of shortcuts of a shortcut tree\nis the number of shortcuts of its unique induced Hamiltonian path. Let $t(n)$\ndenote the largest integer such that every tournament with $n$ vertices has a\nspanning shortcut tree with at least $t(n)$ shortcuts. We almost determine the\nasymptotic growth of $t(n)$ as it is proved that $\\Theta(n\\log^2n) \\ge\nt(n)-\\frac{1}{2}\\binom{n}{2} \\ge \\Theta(n \\log n)$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 29 Sep 2020 13:11:43 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-09-30"}
